to mainstream cinema with a celebrity cast yet to be revealed. Partly inspired by the coronavirus pandemic, the announcement comes at a time when cinemas all over the world have begun to reopen their doors to a tentative public. With its release set for early 2021, the motion picture is definitely on the list of blockbusters likely to draw audiences worldwide out of their homes and back to the cinemas. Vanguard So far, only one Nollywood movie has premiered in Los Angeles. Flower Girl, a romantic comedy film set and shot in Lagos, was screened at the Hollywood Black Film Festival in 2013 February 25, 2017 In "Entertainment" When the likes of Hubert Ogunde, Jab Adu, Ola Balogun, Moses Olaiya (Baba Sala), Eddie Ugbomah and other great filmmakers of yesteryears began what is today known as the Nigerian movie industry, otherwise called Nollywood in the 60s, not many people envisaged the boom that greeted the industry over the… October 10, 2015 In "Home Video People" US cinemas canceled screenings, including a red-carpet New York premiere, of a madcap comedy ''The Interview'' that offended North Korea, after mysterious computer hackers issued a chilling threat. Hollywood studio Sony Pictures said it is not pulling the film, but is leaving it to theater chains to decide whether to… December 17, 2014 In "Showtime People"